Copyright (c) [YEAR] [Your Name / Company Name]. All Rights Reserved.

This software and associated documentation files (the "Software") are the
proprietary property of the copyright holder. No part of the Software may be
copied, modified, distributed, sublicensed, or used to create derivative
works without prior written permission from the copyright holder.

This is the default choice for this project because it's being built as a
commercial product — you generally don't want a permissive license (MIT,
Apache 2.0) on code you intend to sell, since that would legally let anyone
else copy, modify, and redistribute (even resell) it freely.

## If you actually want this to be open source

Replace this file with a standard license instead:
- **MIT** — most permissive; anyone can use, modify, and sell it, only
  attribution required. Use this if you want maximum adoption and don't plan
  to monetize the code itself.
- **Apache 2.0** — like MIT, but includes an explicit patent grant. Common for
  larger open source projects.
- **AGPL-3.0** — requires anyone who runs a modified version as a network
  service to release their source too. Common for projects that want to stay
  open but prevent a company from taking the code closed-source.

Get real license text from https://choosealicense.com — don't hand-write a
license yourself; use the actual, legally-vetted text.

## One more thing worth knowing

A license file doesn't automatically apply per-file — if this repo has
mixed licensing (e.g., you open-source the Android app's architecture example
but keep the backend proprietary), say so explicitly per top-level folder
(android-app/LICENSE, backend/LICENSE) rather than relying on one root file
to cover everything correctly.
